<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by the Coalition of Care and support Providers in Scotland</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written e</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">vidence </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">submitted by the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Coalition of Care and support Providers in Scotland</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.0 </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.1</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">CCPS is the Coalition of Care and support Providers in Scotland. Its membership </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">   </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">comprises more than 70 of the most substantial providers of care and support in Scotland’s voluntary sector, supporting approximately </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">350</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">,000 people and their families, employing around 4</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">,000 staff and managing a combined total income of over £1.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">bn, of w</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">hich an average of 7</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">8</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">% per member organisation relates to service provision that is commissioned, purchased or otherwise funded by the public purse. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.2</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">CCPS members provide services right across the spectrum of care and support, including services for o</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">lder people; children</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, young people</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> and families; adults with physical and learning disabilities</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, sensory impairment, dementia, acquired brain or spinal injury</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">; and people facing a range of challenges in their lives, including mental health problems, addic</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">tions and involvement in the criminal justice system.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.3</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Housing Support Enabling </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Unit </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">(HSEU) </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">works with providers of housing support across Scotland across the voluntary and private sectors and has done so since 2004. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.4</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The Criminal Justice Volu</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ntary Sector Forum (CJVSF) promote</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> the role of the voluntary sector within criminal justice and support</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> voluntary sector providers working in the field of criminal justice in Scotland to increase the impact of their activities.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.0 </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.1</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Vulnerable people across Scotland face growing difficulties accessing and sustaining the housing and support they need due to the cumulative impact of welfare reform.  </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Providers of housing and housing support have concerns about the following aspects of we</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">lfare reform:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">the impact of the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">spare room subsidy</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> (the ‘bedroom tax’</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">lack of availability of one bedroom properties in the social rented sector</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">lack of options for people with support needs </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">who do not live in supported housing and are subject </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">to the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">‘bedroom tax’ where it is not deemed appropriate to take in a lodger and where it is either not possible or not appropriate to move to a smaller property</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">whilst </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">some supported housing</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> is exempt from the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">‘bedroom tax’, Universal Credit and the benefit cap</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">a substantial amount of supported housing does not constitute</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> Supported Exempt Accommodatio</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">n and so becomes subject to these aspects of welfare reform</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">impact </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">on</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> those</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> using</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> criminal justice services </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">increasing use and pressure on</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> support and advice </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">service</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> provided by the voluntary sector </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">increasing use of sanctions is forcing vulnerable people to look for crisis payments or turn to food banks</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">difficulties in accessing move on accommodation for people who have been homeless and are living in suppor</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ted housing</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> which in turn makes it more difficult for homeless people to access supported housing</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">whilst </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">vulnerable people are to be assisted to access and manage benefits under the Local Support Services Framework</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> there needs to be further clarity about</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> who is entitled to this help and for how long</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.0 </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The impact of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">changes to the way housing costs are dealt with under welfare reform</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.1</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">One of the changes which has not yet been fully implemented but which is causing some concern is the plan to pay housing costs through a monthly payment directly to the tenant rather than to the landlord.  </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">re have been various</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> direct payments demonstrat</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ion projects</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> across the UK and they</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> have highlighted an increase in rent arrears. Arrears across the demonstration </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">projects ranged from 3% to 12%. In Scotland</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, Dun</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">edin Canmore has been a </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">de</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">monstrator project and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">has found that ‘</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">engagement, advice on budget</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ing and financial inclusion will involve markedly more intense housing management resource commitment and staff liaison than has traditionally been the case’</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">This could have significant cost implications in terms of housing management at a time when renta</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">l income is under increasing pressure.   </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">In addition, we are aware that during this demonstration project a dedicated Citizens Advice Bureau adviser was made available to assist tenants and we are concerned that this level of resource will not be available</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> to other registered social landlords on full roll out. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.4</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Direct payment</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> is</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> just one aspect of welfare reform; there are other aspects</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, such as the expectation that claimants will submit benefit applications online</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> which will have an impact on the way </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">in which </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">claimants obtain assistance </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">to meet </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">housing costs</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> and will impact on the way local services </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">provide support to do so</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Under the Local Support Service Framework</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">(LSSF) </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">various groups of people</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, including those with support needs,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">may not be </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">expected to manage direct payments</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> and digital access at least</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> initially.  Th</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">is approach is to be welcomed.  </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">We urge that further detail be provided to set out exactly who will be eligible for this different approach and for how long so as to avoid unneces</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">sary </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">confusion which will serve</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> only to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">disempower vulnerable claimants further.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">  </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">This is particularly important for those people using short term supported accommodation and the providers of those services including homeless hostels and womens refuges.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">.5</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">are aware</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> that under th</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">e LSSF, local partnerships are to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">be formed to assess and plan services to help claimants who require support to deal with the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">changes t</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">o the welfare system and that these partnerships may involve the voluntary sector. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">We have already provided some input into the DWP’s plans to use ‘keyworkers’ as a means of providing the assistance that vulnerable claimants will require.  </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">We urge that a distinction between advice work and support work be maintained.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">  </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Already we are awar</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">e that </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">many housing support services are working with people who face increasingly complex issues around managing money and budgeting and there is </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">a risk</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> that support services are being diverted away from essential work on other </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">important daily living skil</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ls and social skills. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.6</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">note that the statutory issues relating to the claimant commitment </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">will be dealt with separately</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">from the local partnerships set out in</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> the LSSF</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">We are already aware</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, however,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">that the support the voluntary sector ha</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">s been </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">offering to claimants can be negatively </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">impact</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> up</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">on by the requirements of the</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> DWP’s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> ‘claimant commitment’. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">One of the ways voluntary agencies have tried to help claimants has been to provide access to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">computers and the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">internet. The numbers of people t</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">hat have been able to use this facility has </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">been restricted</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> by a requirement in some areas that claimants show they have been using the internet to job search on a full time basis.  </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">We would suggest that statutory agencies (DWP and Work Programme) become i</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">nvolved with local partnerships at an appropriate level to ensure the support services, planned and delivered locally, are available and effective for all those who need them.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.7</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">In Scotland the ‘bedroom tax’ has affected 82,500 people</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">.  This figure is somewhat lower than initially predicted due in part to the efforts made by social landlords to assist their tenants </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">move if at all possible. The scope for more people to move to smaller properties is</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, however,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> greatly limited by the la</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ck of smaller properties.  It is estimated that 20,000 one bedroom properties will become available </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">in the social rented sector in Scotland </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">over the next year but 60,000 </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">of the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">people affected by the ‘bedroom tax’ would need to move to a </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">one bedroom proper</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ty to avoid the penalty</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> plus around 23,000 homeless households require a one bedroom property in a year.  </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">It is evident that the ‘bedroom tax’ has created additional demand for a property type in short supply.  It is of particular concern that disabled peo</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ple are being disproportionately affected by this penalty; 80% (63,500) of households in Scotland affected by the ‘bedroom tax’ include an adult with a disability under the </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Disability Discrimination Act.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.8</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> There </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">are 3,200 single-bed households in City </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">of Edinburgh Council area currently seeking housing &amp; only approximately 900 tenures available from local authority and registered social landlord allocations.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">In one week in May</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">32 one bedroom social rented properties were advertised in Edinburgh, with a</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">n average of 121 bids per property through its choice based lettings system.  Of these 32 properties:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">4 were sheltered housing</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">4 were amenity properties or had some sort of age restriction (usually 55 and over)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">8 were on the ground floor</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Of the 16 re</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">maining properties there was an average of 149 bids per property.  This highlights the particular challenge that working age single people or couples may face in obtaining one bedroom accommodation.  This could be a particular issue for ex-offenders seekin</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">g to find settled accommodation; this is known to be an important factor in reducing the risk of re-offending.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.8</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Disabled people living in properties which have housing adaptations are not exempt from the penalty and are being forced to make </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">very </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">difficult decisions about whether to look for another home or not.  To gain assistance with the penalty </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">a disabled person</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> can apply to their local authority for a discretionary housing payment</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> but there is not entitlement to an award and even if one is mad</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">e it will be</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> time limited </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">award with no future award</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> guaranteed.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">We urge that disabled people whose homes have housing adaptations be exempt from the ‘bedroom tax’.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.9</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">We note that children are not expected to share bedrooms with disabled siblings.  </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">W</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">e would </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">also </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">urge that couples who cannot share a bedroom because of illness or a disability of one of both parties also be exempt.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.0 </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Supported Housing</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.1</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Supported housing will be dealt with separately from the Universal Credit system initially </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">but</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> a new system will be developed in the future (2014 onwards) and it is likely that the Westminster Government will devolve funding to Scotland for supported housing. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The future funding of supported housing for those who require assistance to meet housing </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">costs is uncertain.  There is particular concern about the future financial stability of supported housing in respect of:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:25.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">the removal of individual entitlement to assistance to pay housing related costs;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:25.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">the possibility that assistance with housing related</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> costs will be subject to </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">     </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">unringfenced funding at a local level;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:25.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">the level of any future devolved budget and the risk th</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">at it may not fully reflect the </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">     </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">current cost of supported housing. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.2</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">In the meantime some supported housing in Scotland </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">appears to be subject to aspects of welfare reform such as the ‘bedroom tax’</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> despite the Westminster Government’s stated intention to exempt supported housing from them.  The reason for this lies with the decision to restrict the definition of supported h</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ousing to that of Supported Exempt Accommodation</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> (SEA).  Unfortunately SEA</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:25.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">does not include supported housing owned and let by local authorities. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:25.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">lacks clarity about situations where the landlord is not also the support provider.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.3</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">A joint survey</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> undertaken by the HSEU, the Scottish Federation and Housing Associations and Homeless Action Scotland in March 2013 found that many supported housing providers anticipated difficulty in gaining exemptions from aspects of welfare reform</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> such as the bedroo</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">m tax</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> because of the criteria associated with Supported Exempt Accommodation.  The survey found that:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:25.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">42% of respondents (13 respondents) thought that some or all of</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">their supported </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">     </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">housing services would not fall within the definition</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">of SEA. This </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">could mean that some vulnerable people in Scotland will not be able to meet housing related costs associated with supported housing. </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:25.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Most types of supported housing appeared to fall outside the</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">definition of SEA to </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0.75pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">some extent. Supported housing aimed</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">at</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> people with ment</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">al health problems; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">      </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">people with </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">learning</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">disabilities; people with physical disabilities and homeless</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">resettlement projects appear most likely not to meet the criteria for</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">SEA.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.4</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The DWP has acknowledged the need to update the existing definition of Supported Exempt Accommodation and while we welcome this decision we are concerned that </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">indications so far suggest that </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">local authority owned accommodation will not be included in any r</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">evision.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.5</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Almost a third of refuge accommodation is owned by local authorities in Scotland and does not qualify as exempt. The majority of local authorities have continued to exempt this </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">accommodation from the under occupation charge for this financi</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">al year while </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">they await </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">the outcome of the DWP’s </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">review of</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> housing benefit and supported accommodation. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> some area</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">s, however,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> there has </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">already </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">be</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">en an impact on refuge services, for instance in one area where a refuge has been assessed as not qualifyi</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ng as exempt (although this is being challenged) it is now unable to offer a service to women and children unless they would qualify for a 3 bedroom flat under the ‘bedroom tax’ rules.  In other areas </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Women</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">’s Aid services are being advised that the local a</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">uthority grant they have come to rely on will be reduced in the next year to offset the costs of covering the current benefit shortfall caused by the ‘bedroom tax’.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.6</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Refuge services in Scotland are already unable to meet demand; </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">a recent </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">annual census </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">day survey found that 2 out of 3 women were unable to get a refuge space for themselves and their children because of the lack of safe or suitable space.</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">  Where women are not able to access refuge for themselves and their children when they need to they ma</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">y be at risk of returning to abusive partners or forced to accept unsuitable bed and breakfast accommodation through a local authority which will no longer have access to appropriate temporary self-contained accommodation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.7</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">The ‘bedroom tax’ is already</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> limiting the options for people facing homelessness and could impact on the availability of supported accommodation provided through the ‘Housing First’ model which is being piloted in Glasgow by Turning Point.  Under this model</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> people facing homelessness avoid using temporary accommodation whilst accessing the support they need.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">  The ‘bedroom tax’ restrict</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> available accommodation for single people and couples facing homelessness</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> and result in greater demand being placed on te</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">mporary accommodation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.8</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Whilst local authorities may decide to prioritise some assistance for supported housing services that do not meet the SEA criteria through the Discretionary Housing Payments (DHP) this can only be regarded as a short term soluti</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">on given the intense pressure on DHP. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">This increase in pressure was evidenced by t</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">he</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> number of applications for Discretiona</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">y Housing Payments </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Glasgow City Council, for instance,</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">with</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> 5,501 applications for DHP in April 2013 compared with just 1,437 in </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">April 2012.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Although</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> the Scottish Government has set out plans to increase the amount available for discretionary housing payments in 2013/14 t</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">his is not a long term solution.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.0 </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Severe poverty</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.1</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">There is growing evidence that people are being </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">forced into greater poverty due to welfare refor</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">m.  The Tru</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ssell Trust has been highlighting an increasing use of foodbanks</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> and Citizens Advice services have reported that increasing numbers of people are coming to them in ‘extreme poverty’.  Whilst the v</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">oluntary sector is responding to this growing demand it is of great concern that people have to turn to them for help to survive.  Indeed the Stirling Citizen Advice Bureau has recently developed a ‘Survival Guide’ to help people deal with ‘no money, no fo</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">od and no power’.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.2</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Support workers are working with an increasing number of people who face benefit sanctions.  This is a particular issue for people required to demonstrate to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">J</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ob </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">entre staff that they are looking for work.  There appears to be a </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">lack of consistency between job centres about what constitutes suitable evidence. </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Young care leavers and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">young people in transition</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">are facing major problems with sanctions and conditionality because of the p</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">articular challenges they face</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">and we would urge that their needs are given further consideration in </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ine with those set out by the National Care Advisory Service (NCAS)</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Other people have faced sanctions relating to attendance at medical assessments and have had to wait 8 weeks witho</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ut benefit payments until the outcome of their appeal.  In this case a crisis grant was obtained through the Scottish Welfare Fund but was not sufficient to last 8 weeks.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">There is concern that once a sanction</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> has been applied (even if it has</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> clearly been a</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">pplied wro</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">ngly), there is nothing any organisation or authority can do to prompt the DWP or Job C</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">entre to </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">lift the sanction.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.3</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">People </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">who</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> do not qualify for an advance benefit payment nor for a payment through the Scottish Welfare Fund are being advised to go to a food bank.  This is particularly difficult in rural areas where people may not have the means to travel the distances involved.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.0 </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Criminal Justice </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">practitioners</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.1</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Criminal justice practitioners have highlighted a number of ways these reforms </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">re </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">impacting on their service users.  Practitioners report particular concerns that service users </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">e </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">struggling to meet their day-to-day living costs and many </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">re </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">unable to afford any increase in housing costs arising from the ‘Bedroom Tax’.  At the same time, a lack of </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">alternative housing available locally mean</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> that the individuals concerned </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">not have</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> the option to move to a smaller property and </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">re </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">therefore facing rent arrears. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.2</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">Practitioners also anticipat</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt"> that the ‘Bedroom Tax’ could impact on families that have a family member going to prison.   An individual is eligible for housing benefit </span><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">when they are in prison:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">up to 52 weeks awaiting trial or sentence;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">up to 13 weeks if sentenced and likely to return home within 13 weeks.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">If an individual is in prison for longer than these periods, then they will not be eligible to claim housing benefit and the ‘Bedroom Tax’ could apply to the family. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">26 September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Tahoma; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">7</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Welfare Reform (Further Provisions) (Scotl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">and) Act 2013, Initial Report </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">. Available at: </span><a href="http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Resource/0042/00426405.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Resource/0042/00426405.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> (accessed 25th September 2013)</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Supported housing in Scotland and the extent to which it may be exempt from various aspects of w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">elfare reform, March 2013, HSEU. Available at: </span><a href="http://www.ccpscotland.org/assets/files/hseu/Publications/HSEU%20Research/SEA%20survey%20report.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.ccpscotland.org/assets/files/hseu/Publications/HSEU%20Research/SEA%20survey%20report.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> (accessed at 25</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> September 2013)</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Turning Po</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">int and the Housing First pilot, September 2012.  Available at:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.turningpointscotland.com/news/delegates-arrive-for-housing-first-event/#"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.turningpointscotland.com/news/delegates-arrive-for-housing-first-event/#</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> (accessed 26</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> September 2013)</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Inside Housing, 14</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> May 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">.  Available at: </span><a href="http://www.insidehousing.co.uk/tenancies/councils-swamped-with-demand-for-welfare-fund/6526941.article"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.insidehousing.co.uk/t</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">e</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">nancies/councils-swamped-with-demand-for-welfare-fund/6526941.article</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> (accessed 26th September 2013)</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> ‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Bedroom Tax</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">’:Early Impacts, SFHA June 2013.  Avaiable at: </span><a href="http://www.sfha.co.uk/component/option,com_docman/Itemid,37/gid,3030/task,doc_download/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.sfha.co.uk/component/</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family